{"cursor":"2325","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox Union |name= SARTUC |country= |affiliation= |members= |full_name=\nSouth Asian Regional Trade Union Council |native_name= |image= |founded= 1988\n|current= |head= |dissolved_date= |dissolved_state= |merged_into= |office=\n|people= |website= |footnotes= }}  The 'South Asian Regional Trade Union Council (SARTUC)' is a\nfederation of national trade union centers whose geographic scope covers South\nAsia. SARTUC's mission is to promote workers' rights within its member\nnations. [http://www.gurn.info/topic/trade/icftu_0604.pdf International\nConfederation of Free Trade Unions. The Spread of Bilateral and Regional Trade\nAgreements. June 2004.]\n\nThe South Asian Regional Trade Union Council was formed in January 1988 by some\nof the affiliates of the International Confederation of Free Trade Unions (now\nthe ITUC) in countries belonging to the South Asian Association for Regional\nCooperation (SAARC)âAfghanistan, Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, Maldives, Nepal,\nPakistan and Sri Lanka. The Indian trade union center Hind Mazdoor Sabha, was\none of the founding members of SARTUC. [http://www-\nold.itcilo.org/actrav/english/calendar/2001/A3_2380/work/Country_reports/india.-\ndoc Pijush Chakraborty. \"Trade Union Training on Information Technology.\" Hind\nMazdoor Sabha. Turin/Vienna: February 19, 2001âMarch 16, 2001.]\n\nNazrul Islam Khan (then-president of the Bangladesh Metal Workers' Federation)\nwas SAR-TUC's general-secretary in 2003. [http://www.ilo.org/public/english-\n/region/asro/bangkok/public/releases/yr2003/pr0326.htm \"Shipbreaking Guidelines\nCharting New Waters.\" ILO News. October 15, 2003.]\n","linknr":115,"url":"South_Asian_Regional_Trade_Union_Council","recorded":1375090197,"links":["/w/index.php?title=South_Asian_Regional_Trade_Union_Council&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=South_Asian_Regional_Trade_Union_Council&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/op